etymology_text:
From Middle English seen, from Old English sēon (“to see, look, behold, perceive, observe, discern, understand, know”), from Proto-West Germanic *sehwan, from Proto-Germanic *sehwaną (“to see”), from Proto-Indo-European *sekʷ- (“to see, notice”).
Cognates
Cognate with West Frisian sjen (“to see”), Dutch zien (“to see”), Low German sehn, German sehen (“to see”), Danish, Swedish and Norwegian Bokmål se (“to see”), Norwegian Nynorsk sjå (“to see”), and more distantly with Latin sīgnum (“sign, token”), Albanian shih (“look at, see”) imperative of shoh (“to see”).

raw_glosses: To witness or observe by personal experience.

examples.text: Now I've seen it all!
I have been blind since birth and I love to read Braille. When the books arrive in from the library, I can’t wait to see what stories they have sent me.
Uerely, verely I ſay vnto you, If a man keepe my ſaying, hee ſhall neuer ſee death.

examples.text: […] And remember this, 'scape-gallows,' said Ralph, menacing him with his hand, 'that if we meet again, and you so much as notice me by one begging gesture, you shall see the inside of a jail once more […]
examples.ref: 1838 March – 1839 October, Charles Dickens, The Life and Adventures of Nicholas Nickleby, London: Chapman and Hall,[…], published 1839, OCLC 1057107260, page 434

glosses: To perceive or detect someone or something with the eyes, or as if by sight.

examples.text: They're blind to the damage they do, but someday they'll see.

raw_glosses: (transitive; ergative) To be the setting or time of.

examples.text: The 20th century saw humanity's first space exploration.
1999 saw the release of many great films.
It seems as if every passing year sees the mainstream embrace a longtime cult-favorite alternative rock band.
examples.ref: 1995-06-03, David Sprague, “Buffalo Tom Reaches Crossroads: EastWest Trio At Make-Or-Break Point”, in Billboard, volume 107, number 22, page 9

glosses: To be the setting or time of.

raw_glosses: (by extension) To ensure that something happens, especially while witnessing it.

examples.text: I'll see you hang for this!  I saw that they didn't make any more trouble.

glosses: To ensure that something happens, especially while witnessing it.

examples.text: I saw the old lady safely across the road.
You can see yourself out.

raw_glosses: (gambling, transitive) To respond to another player's bet with a bet of equal value.

examples.text: I'll see your twenty dollars and raise you ten.

glosses: To respond to another player's bet with a bet of equal value.

raw_glosses: To determine by trial or experiment; to find out (if or whether).

examples.text: I'll come over later and see if I can fix your computer.
You think I can't beat you in a race, eh? We'll see.

glosses: To determine by trial or experiment; to find out (if or whether).

raw_glosses: (used in the imperative) To reference or to study for further details.

examples.text: Step 4: In the system, check out the laptop to the student (see: "Logging Resources" in the Tutor Manual).
For a complete proof of the Poincaré conjecture, see Appendix C.

glosses: To reference or to study for further details.

raw_glosses: To examine something closely, or to utilize something, often as a temporary alternative.

examples.text: Can I see that lighter for a second? Mine just quit working.

glosses: To examine something closely, or to utilize something, often as a temporary alternative.

raw_glosses: To include as one of something's experiences.

examples.text: The equipment has not seen usage outside of our projects.
I saw military service in Vietnam.

glosses: To include as one of something's experiences.
